Here is a C++ program to find the nth Fibonacci number using recursion:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

unsigned long long fibonacci(unsigned int n) {
    if (n <= 1)
        return n;
    else
        return fibonacci(n - 1) + fibonacci(n - 2);
}

int main() {
    unsigned int n;
    cout << "Enter the value of n: ";
    cin >> n;

    if (n <= 0) {
        cout << "Invalid input. Please enter a positive integer." << endl;
    } else {
        unsigned long long result = fibonacci(n);
        cout << "The " << n << "th Fibonacci number is: " << result << endl;
    }

    return 0;
}
```

This program prompts the user to enter the value of n. It then calculates the nth Fibonacci number using a recursive function. The Fibonacci sequence is defined such that each number is the sum of the two preceding numbers, usually starting with 0 and 1.

Please note that the Fibonacci function has a time complexity of O(2^n) and may run slowly for large values of n. To improve performance, consider using an iterative solution or a recursive solution with memoization.

